services.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XMPP\n','2013-11-11 12:21:50','en'),(736,'Protocol::Translation',3,'update',NULL,'---\ntitle: OTR\ndescription: \"Off-the-Record Messaging, commonly referred to as OTR, is a cryptographic\n  protocol that provides strong encryption for instant messaging conversations. OTR\n  uses a combination of the AES symmetric-key algorithm, the Diffie–Hellman key exchange,\n  and the SHA-1 hash function. In addition to authentication and encryption, OTR provides\n  perfect forward secrecy and malleable encryption.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe primary motivation\n  behind the protocol was providing deniability for the conversation participants\n  while keeping conversations confidential, like a private conversation in real life,\n  or off the record in journalism sourcing.\"\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Off-the-Record_Messaging\nid: 2\ncreated_at: 2013-10-14 16:04:53.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-14 16:04:53.000000000 Z\n','2013-11-11 12:21:52','en'),(737,'Protocol::Translation',3,'update',NULL,'---\nid: 3\nprotocol_id: 2\nlocale: en\ncreated_at: 2013-10-14 16:04:53.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-14 16:04:53.000000000 Z\ntitle: OTR\ndescription: \"Off-the-Record Messaging, commonly referred to as OTR, is a cryptographic\n  protocol that provides strong encryption for instant messaging conversations. OTR\n  uses a combination of the AES symmetric-key algorithm, the Diffie–Hellman key exchange,\n  and the SHA-1 hash function. In addition to authentication and encryption, OTR provides\n  perfect forward secrecy and malleable encryption.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe primary motivation\n  behind the protocol was providing deniability for the conversation participants\n  while keeping conversations confidential, like a private conversation in real life,\n  or off the record in journalism sourcing.\"\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Off-the-Record_Messaging\n','2013-11-11 12:21:52','en'),(738,'Protocol::Translation',4,'update',NULL,'---\ntitle: SIP\ndescription: The Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is a signaling communications protocol,\n  widely used for controlling multimedia communication sessions such as voice and\n  video calls over Internet Protocol (IP) networks.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Session_Initiation_Protocol\nid: 3\ncreated_at: 2013-10-14 16:08:37.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-14 16:08:37.000000000 Z\n','2013-11-11 12:21:53','en'),(739,'Protocol::Translation',4,'update',NULL,'---\nid: 4\nprotocol_id: 3\nlocale: en\ncreated_at: 2013-10-14 16:08:37.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-14 16:08:37.000000000 Z\ntitle: SIP\ndescription: The Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is a signaling communications protocol,\n  widely used for controlling multimedia communication sessions such as voice and\n  video calls over Internet Protocol (IP) networks.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Session_Initiation_Protocol\n','2013-11-11 12:21:53','en'),(740,'Protocol::Translation',5,'update',NULL,'---\ntitle: Tor\ndescription: Tor is free software for enabling online anonymity. Tor directs Internet\n  traffic through a free, worldwide, volunteer network consisting of more than three\n  thousand relays to conceal a user\'s location or usage from anyone conducting network\n  surveillance or traffic analysis. Using Tor makes it more difficult to trace Internet\n  activity, including \"visits to Web sites, online posts, instant messages, and other\n  communication forms\", back to the user and is intended to protect the personal privacy\n  of users, as well as their freedom and ability to conduct confidential business\n  by keeping their internet activities from being monitored.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tor_%28anonymity_network%29\nid: 4\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:57:57.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:57:57.000000000 Z\n','2013-11-11 12:21:54','en'),(741,'Protocol::Translation',5,'update',NULL,'---\nid: 5\nprotocol_id: 4\nlocale: en\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:57:57.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:57:57.000000000 Z\ntitle: Tor\ndescription: Tor is free software for enabling online anonymity. Tor directs Internet\n  traffic through a free, worldwide, volunteer network consisting of more than three\n  thousand relays to conceal a user\'s location or usage from anyone conducting network\n  surveillance or traffic analysis. Using Tor makes it more difficult to trace Internet\n  activity, including \"visits to Web sites, online posts, instant messages, and other\n  communication forms\", back to the user and is intended to protect the personal privacy\n  of users, as well as their freedom and ability to conduct confidential business\n  by keeping their internet activities from being monitored.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tor_%28anonymity_network%29\n','2013-11-11 12:21:54','en'),(742,'Protocol::Translation',6,'update',NULL,'---\ntitle: VoIP\ndescription: Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) is a methodology and group of technologies\n  for the delivery of voice communications and multimedia sessions over Internet Protocol\n  (IP) networks, such as the Internet. Other terms commonly associated with VoIP are\n  IP telephony, Internet telephony, voice over broadband (VoBB), broadband telephony,\n  IP communications, and broadband phone service.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_telephony\nid: 5\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:58:25.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:58:25.000000000 Z\n','2013-11-11 12:21:56','en'),(743,'Protocol::Translation',6,'update',NULL,'---\nid: 6\nprotocol_id: 5\nlocale: en\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:58:25.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:58:25.000000000 Z\ntitle: VoIP\ndescription: Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) is a methodology and group of technologies\n  for the delivery of voice communications and multimedia sessions over Internet Protocol\n  (IP) networks, such as the Internet. Other terms commonly associated with VoIP are\n  IP telephony, Internet telephony, voice over broadband (VoBB), broadband telephony,\n  IP communications, and broadband phone service.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_telephony\n','2013-11-11 12:21:56','en'),(744,'Protocol::Translation',7,'update',NULL,'---\ntitle: ZRTP\ndescription: ZRTP (composed of Z and Real-time Transport Protocol) is a cryptographic\n  key-agreement protocol to negotiate the keys for encryption between two end points\n  in a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) phone telephony call based on the Real-time\n  Transport Protocol. It uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange and the Secure Real-time\n  Transport Protocol (SRTP) for encryption. ZRTP was developed by Phil Zimmermann,\n  with help from Bryce Wilcox-O\'Hearn, Colin Plumb, Jon Callas and Alan Johnston and\n  was submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) by Phil Zimmermann,\n  Jon Callas and Alan Johnston on March 5, 2006 and published on April 11, 2011 as\n  RFC 6189.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZRTP\nid: 6\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:59:51.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:59:51.000000000 Z\n','2013-11-11 12:21:57','en'),(745,'Protocol::Translation',7,'update',NULL,'---\nid: 7\nprotocol_id: 6\nlocale: en\ncreated_at: 2013-10-15 06:59:51.000000000 Z\nupdated_at: 2013-10-15 06:59:51.000000000 Z\ntitle: ZRTP\ndescription: ZRTP (composed of Z and Real-time Transport Protocol) is a cryptographic\n  key-agreement protocol to negotiate the keys for encryption between two end points\n  in a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) phone telephony call based on the Real-time\n  Transport Protocol. It uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange and the Secure Real-time\n  Transport Protocol (SRTP) for encryption. ZRTP was developed by Phil Zimmermann,\n  with help from Bryce Wilcox-O\'Hearn, Colin Plumb, Jon Callas and Alan Johnston and\n  was submitted to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) by Phil Zimmermann,\n  Jon Callas and Alan Johnston on March 5, 2006 and published on April 11, 2011 as\n  RFC 6189.\nurl: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZRTP